[4] Uganda Virus Research Institute resumes testing
Date: Thu 20 Oct 2022
Source: Monitor [abridged, edited]
https://www.monitor.co.ug/uganda/news/national/virus-research-centre-resumes-ebola-testing-3992020


Virus research centre resumes Ebola testing
-------------------------------------------
The Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) in Entebbe has resumed Ebola testing after the Ministry of Health had blocked it 2 weeks ago.

Prof Pontiano Kaleebu, the UVRI executive director, said they had now resolved the matter with the ministry.

"There were some misunderstandings which we have sorted. We had a good meeting last week on Friday [14 Oct 2022] with the minister and other partners and we agreed on moving forward. UVRI is back to testing many samples coming from Kampala but also continues to be the reference laboratory to support the mobile lab," Prof Kaleebu said on Tuesday [18 Oct 2022].

He made the revelation while unveiling the new USD 500 000 (Shs 1.9b) National Institute of Health (NIH) laboratories supported by the US government.

The laboratories will focus on conducting research on viruses of animal origin that infect humans. The labs in partnership with NIH will also strengthen collaboration with international scientists.

"Our lab is a national and regional reference not only for Ebola. We have a plan that our team will be in Mubende this week to support the mobile labs in terms of training but also continue with quality control and assurance so that we do a good job," he added.

[Byline: Eve Muganga]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[The disagreement between Uganda Virus Research Institute (UVRI) and the Health Ministry over disease surveillance mandates and associated deals, had sparked confusion in Ebola virus testing. To read about the problem see https://www.monitor.co.ug/uganda/news/national/inside-the-uvri-moh-fight-over-ebola-testing-3980724]. It is good the problem has been resolved and testing may proceed. - Mod.LK]

