[5] Comment on mortality rate
Date: Tue 18 Oct 2022
From: Allen Lenoir <alenoir165@aol.com> [edited]


re: ProMED Ebola update (30): Uganda 20221018.8706223
-----------------------------------------------------
With 78 cases and 39 deaths, why is the mortality [case fatality] rate 63%?

On 14 Oct 2022 BNO News reported
Total cases: 78 (58 conf.)
Total deaths: 39 (19 conf.)
Total recovered: 23 (+3)
Case fatality rate: 63%

--
Allen Lenoir, MD
<alenoir165@aol.com>

[ProMED thanks Dr Lenoir for his comment.

The numbers have been hard to pin down, as evidenced in the daily reports. The numbers from BNO News 14 Oct 2022, that is, 39 deaths/78 cases, with 63% mortality come directly from the report. There are now 2 more cases and sadly 1 additional death of a healthcare worker, so 40/80 or holding at 50% mortality of confirmed plus probable cases. I am not sure how BNO calculated 63% no matter how you work the numbers.

Helen Branswell tweeted, "Good that Uganda is posting #Ebola numbers on the Ministry of Health's site. But they have stripped out 20 probable cases -- people with Ebola-like symptoms & likely epi links who died without being tested. They would bring the total to 80 cases, 44 deaths," The CFR would thus be 55%.

The LA Times (17 Oct 2022) wrote, "There are 54 confirmed and 20 probable Ebola cases in the recent outbreak, as well as 39 deaths, according to the World Health Organization (12 Oct 2022)." That is a 72% mortality [case fatality] rate of confirmed cases (53% confirmed plus probable). But this is a little out of date now.

The Reuters report in [1] above from US government sources states 60 infected people and 44 deaths (73%). The WHO numbers are 60 confirmed and 20 probable cases since the outbreak began last month (September 2022), and 44 deaths (55% confirmed plus probable). The health ministry said there are now 64 lab-confirmed cases and 25 deaths among confirmed patients (39% confirmed only).

I don't think we'll have strong numbers on the case fatality rate until the outbreak is over, confirmatory tests are complete, and numbers are tallied. But mortality appears to be in the range of 39%-73%, both too high. Antivirals are on the way, and a vaccine trial will begin shortly. Let's hope both are successful. - Mod.LK

